# How to Delete Un-Needed Apps in Heroku When You Reach Your Free Limit.

1. 1.To clear Heroku apps you are no longer using, log into heroku.com and click on "Personal apps".

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. 2.Heroku doesn't list your app names so click on one, probably with ZZZ listed.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. 3.Click on the menu in the top right corner.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. 4.Choose "Open app".

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. 5.You can view your app and decide if it's one you can delete.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. 6.Click on "Settings" while in the app.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1.
Scroll down and click on "Delete app". ![](data:image/*;base64,)
2. 8.Enter Heroku's name of your app when prompted (which is also listed in the message) and click "Delete app".

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)









1. 9.Successful when you are taken back to the "Personal apps" page.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

If you accidentally delete the wrong one, you will need to delete the remote user you already set up and recreate your remote user.

Use git remote rm -v to list your remote users to confirm you have a heroku app created.

Use the git remote rm command to remove a remote URL from your repository.

The git remote rm command takes one argument:

So, in this case you would add "heroku" to the command to delete your remote user.

git remote rm heroku

Now you can recreate your heroku remote user.
